.START 

Stock prices extended their recent gains in unusually slow trading related to the observances of Columbus Day and Yom Kippur. 

The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which climbed a total of 92.70 points last week and hasn't yet posted a loss this month, added 5.89 to 2791.41 -- its fifth consecutive all-time high. 

Continued buying in International Business Machines, rebounding from its retreat last week to a 52-week low, and solid gains among several other blue-chip issues boosted the average even though profit-taking weighed down some of last week's best performers. 

New York Stock Exchange volume failed to surpass the 100 million-share mark for only the second time this year, as just 86,810,000 shares were traded.
The Big Board's low for the year came July 3, the session before Independence Day, when 68.8 million shares changed hands. 

"You can't really base anything on today's action," said Jack Baker, head of the equity block trading desk at Shearson Lehman Hutton. "There's just literally nothing going on." 

Broader averages kept their October win streaks alive and established another round of record highs.
Standard & Poor's 500-Stock Index rose 1.02 to 359.80, the Dow Jones Equity Market Index rose 0.87 to 337.63 and the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index went up 0.40 to 199.34.
Advancers topped decliners on the Big Board by 705 to 657. 

The Dow Jones Transportation Average posted its ninth consecutive advance by rising 13.87 to 1518.49, reflecting gains among airline stocks following a report that money manager Michael Steinhardt is seeking to boost the price of USAir Group's stock. 

Profit-taking made its presence felt in the broad market in early trading as prices drifted to session lows, but interest in blue chips and technology issues, including IBM, provided the catalyst for stocks to reverse course.
The Dow industrials peaked in the final half-hour just about four points from 2800.
Once the market returns to full strength today, Mr. Baker said he would expect stocks to continue working their way higher. "I think the trip through 2800 is going to be a quick one," he said. 

USAir, the most active Big Board issue, climbed 3 5/8 to 52 1/4 as 1.7 million shares changed hands in composite trading.
USA Today reported that Steinhardt Partners, which holds an 8.3% stake in the company, hired Wertheim, Schroder & Co. to explore several possibilities for boosting the stock price.
The report also said Steinhardt hasn't ruled out a hostile takeover offer. 

AMR, which owns American Airlines and has received a $120-a-share offer from Donald Trump, rose 1 to 104 3/4 as 1.2 million shares were traded.
UAL, the owner of United Airlines and the target of a $300-a-share buy-out bid from a labor-management group, gained 1 1/4 to 284 1/4.
Delta Air Lines, one of the few major carriers left untouched by the industry's rash of takeovers, climbed 1 3/4 to 81 3/4. 

Among the blue-chip issues falling victim to profit-taking, American Telephone & Telegraph lost 1 to 43 3/4, Coca-Cola Co. eased 1/2 to 70 1/8, Chevron dropped 1 to 65 and Aluminum Co. of America slid 7/8 to 78 3/4. 

Besides IBM, which gained 1 3/4 to 109 1/4, issues in the Dow industrials that offset those losses included Procter & Gamble, which went up 2 3/4 to 131 3/4; Texaco, up 1 1/4 to 54 1/2; American Express, up 7/8 to 39 1/4, and Du Pont, up 1 1/2 to 122.
Philip Morris gained 3/4 to 179 3/8 after trading as low as 177 3/8. 

Compaq Computer proved to be the sharpest gainer among technology issues, as it climbed 6 1/4 to 104 7/8 amid speculation about a new portable computer it plans to introduce next Monday.
Digital Equipment advanced 1 7/8 to 93 1/2, Hewlett-Packard rose 1 1/8 to 51 1/4, Texas Instruments went up 7/8 to 38 3/4 and Motorola added 1 7/8 to 61 3/4. 

American Medical International, which accepted an amended takeover proposal from IMA Holdings, gained 5/8 to 23 7/8 on nearly one million shares.
The investor group lowered the price of its tender offer by $1.50 a share, to $26.50, and reduced the number of shares it would purchase under the offer. 

Walt Disney jumped 6 3/4 to 134 5/8.
Talk of strong demand for the company's offering in Europe of a 51% stake in its Euro Disneyland project attracted foreign buyers to the stock, according to Dow Jones Professional Investor Report. 

Gulf States Utilities rose 5/8 to 14 1/8.
Salomon Brothers, which considers the stock a "speculative buy," repeated the recommendation and said it expects a decision tomorrow from a Louisiana judge setting disallowance costs for the River Bend nuclear plant. 

Weakness on the London stock market hurt Imperial Chemical Industries, which fell 2 3/4 to 75 3/8 amid news of its agreement to sell its U.S. over-the-counter drug operations to a joint venture of Johnson & Johnson and Merck.
The transaction, in which ICI will take over the marketing rights to the anti-depressant drug Elavil, is valued at $450 million. 

Other British-based companies whose stocks lost ground included British Airways, which went down 1 1/4 to 33 3/8; British Steel, down 5/8 to 20 3/4; British Telecom, off 1 1/8 to 42 1/8, and Hanson, down 1/4 to 17 3/8. 

Citicorp rose 7/8 to 35 1/8 on 1.1 million shares.
Kidder Peabody analyst Charles Peabody, who repeated a buy recommendation on the stock, told PIR he expects a fourth-quarter action by the company "that will excite people." Except to say that he rules out an equity offering, he wouldn't elaborate. 

Medtronic gained 1 5/8 to 68 1/4.
The company's board established an employee stock ownership plan and, in a related move, approved the repurchase of as many as 750,000 common shares. 

Tonka slid 1 1/8 to 18 7/8 on news of its proposed offering of 6.5 million common shares, which would increase the number of outstanding shares by more than 80%.
Proceeds would be used to repay debt. 

Petrie Stores, the subject of a feature story in Barron's magazine, went up 3/4 to 26.
Bargain-hunters are being attracted to the stock based on its asset value, the report said; also, there is speculation that 86-year-old Chairman Milton Petrie will bequeath his 60% stake in the company to a charitable foundation, which will then sell the shares. 

Imperial Corp. of America dropped 5/8 to 2 5/8.
In its cover story, Barron's traced the fall of the savings-and-loan company, which the report attributed to mismanagement, inadequate regulation, organized crime and questionable accounting. 

Jackpot Enterprises fell 2 1/4 to 13 7/8.
The company reported that its earnings for the June quarter were below the year-earlier level. 

The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index extended its recent winning streak, which has now produced 14 consecutive advances and eight consecutive alltime highs, by gaining 0.59 to 396.52.
Volume totaled 8,230,000 shares. 

Bolar Pharmaceutical dropped 1 5/8 to 20 3/4.
The company recalled its generic form of Macrodantin, an anti-infective drug, after the Food and Drug Administration presented it with evidence that the brand-name version had been submitted as its own for testing.
Bolar denied the charges. 

